{"title_page": "Port Dover, Ontario", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2015}}\n\n{{short description|Community of Norfolk County, Ontario, Canada}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Port Dover, Ontario\n|settlement_type        = Unincorporated hamlet in Norfolk County\n|other_name             =\n|native_name            =  <!-- for cities whose native name is not in English -->\n|nickname               =\n|motto                  = \n|image_skyline          = Boats moored at Port Dover, Ontario.jpg|frameless|upright=1.15\n|imagesize              =\n|image_caption          = Boats moored at Port Dover, Ontario.\n|image_flag             =\n|flag_size              =\n|image_seal             =\n|seal_size              =\n|image_shield           =\n|shield_size            =\n|image_blank_emblem     =\n|blank_emblem_size      =\n|image_map              =\n|mapsize                =\n|map_caption            =\n|image_map1             =\n|mapsize1               =\n|map_caption1           =\n|image_dot_map          =\n|dot_mapsize            =\n|dot_map_caption        =\n|dot_x =  |dot_y =\n|pushpin_map            = Canada Southern Ontario\n|pushpin_label_position =\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location in southern Ontario\n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = {{CAN}}\n|subdivision_type1      = [[List of Canadian Provinces|Province]]\n|subdivision_name1      = {{ON}}\n|subdivision_name3      =\n|subdivision_type4      =\n|subdivision_name4      =\n|government_type        =\n|leader_title           = Mayor\n|leader_name            = Kristal Chopp\n|leader_title1          = Governing Body\n|leader_name1           = The Council of The Corporation of Norfolk County\n|leader_title2          = [[House of Commons of Canada|MPs]]\n|leader_name2           = [[Diane Finley]] ([[Conservative Party of Canada|Con]])\n|leader_title3          = [[Legislative Assembly|MPPs]]\n|leader_name3           = [[Toby Barrett]] ([[Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario|PC]])\n|leader_title4          =\n|leader_name4           =\n|established_title      = Established\n|established_date       = 1794 as Dover Mills\n|established_title2     = \n|established_date2      = 1974 (Regional Municipality of Haldimand-Norfolk)\n|established_title3     = Amalgamated into Norfolk County\n|established_date3      = 2001 (Single-tier municipality)\n|area_magnitude         =\n|unit_pref              = <!--Enter: Imperial, if Imperial (metric) is desired-->\n|area_footnotes         = \n|area_total_km2         =\n|area_land_km2          = 9.15\n|area_water_km2         =\n|area_water_percent     =\n|population             = 6161\n|population_as_of       = 2016\n|population_density_km2 = 698.04\n|timezone               = [[North American Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n|utc_offset             = -5\n|timezone_DST           = [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]]\n|utc_offset_DST         = -4\n|coordinates            = {{coord|42|47|12|N|80|12|11|W|region:CA-ON|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_footnotes    =  <!--for references: use <ref> </ref> tags-->\n|elevation_m            = 210\n|postal_code_type       = [[Canadian postal code#Forward sortation areas|Forward sortation area]]\n|postal_code            = [[List of N postal codes of Canada|N0A]]\n|area_code              = [[Area code 519|519]] / [[Area code 226|226]] / \n|website                = [http://www.norfolkcounty.ca/ www.norfolkcounty.ca]\n|footnotes              =\n}}\n{{commons category|Port Dover, Ontario}}\n\n'''Port Dover''' is an unincorporated community and former [[town]] located in [[Norfolk County, Ontario|Norfolk County]], [[Ontario]], Canada on the north shore of [[Lake Erie]].\n\n==Summary==\nPrior to the [[War of 1812]], this community was known as '''Dover Mills'''. This community is the southern terminus for [[Ontario Highway 6]]; located {{convert|480|km|mi|disp=or}} to the south of the Northern Ontario community of [[Baldwin, Ontario|McKerrow]].<ref>{{cite map\n|title     = Road Atlas \u2013 Canada, United States, and Mexico\n|publisher = Peter Heiler Ltd\n|edition   = 2008\n|page      = 17, 19\n|section   = B6\u2013G7, G8\u2013K8, L9, M10\u2013R11}}</ref> This highway stretches northward as a two-lane, undivided highway until the traffic flow increases to four lanes shortly after it departs from [[Caledonia, Ontario|Caledonia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onthighways.com/highway_6_page_1.htm|title=Highway 6 Information for Norfolk County to City of Hamilton|work=Ontario King's Highways|accessdate=July 3, 2007}}</ref> In addition to allowing Port Dover residents direct access to the city of [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]], it also briefly merges with [[Ontario Highway 403|Highway 403]] to allow for access to the [[Royal Botanical Gardens (Ontario)|Royal Botanical Gardens]] and locations on to Toronto.\n\nThe [[postal code|postal]] [[forward sortation area]] is ''N0A''; sharing its [[Canada Post]] service with the western portion of Haldimand County. All residences and businesses within the Port Dover area have a ''583'' in their phone number.\n\nA verified amount of at least 128 species of bird have been discovered in Port Dover from 1956 to 2019; including the [[Indigo Bunting]], the [[Rose-breasted Grosbeak]], and the [[Scarlet Tanager]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://ebird.org/hotspot/L633655?m=&yr=all&changeDate=Set| title = Bird Counts in Port Dover, Ontario | publisher = eBird | date = | accessdate = 2019-05-22}}</ref>\n\nThe second largest of the [[Communities in Norfolk County, Ontario]], Port Dover had a population of 6,161 at the time of the 2016 Census.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=POPC&Code1=0658&Geo2=PR&Code2=47&Data=Count&SearchText=Port%20Dover&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1 |title=Census Profile, 2016 Census Port Dover |publisher=[[Statistics Canada]]|accessdate=March 12, 2019}}</ref> English is spoken by the majority of the residents; with 285 people speaking languages other than English or French. The majority of Port Dover residents were born in Canada, with 515 residents being born in Europe in addition to 10 African-born residents, 70 US-born residents and 70 residents who were born in Asia.<ref>[http://www.citypopulation.de/php/canada-ua-ontario.php?cityid=UA0658 Demographics information] at City Population</ref>\n\nMost people get their television either through [[Shaw Direct]], [[Bell TV]] or [[terrestrial television|over-the-air]]. There is only one channel can be picked up reliably using an outdoor antenna while an additional five channels can be picked up semi-reliably. There are twelve channels that can be picked up over-the-air only during sunny days where clouds are absent.<ref>[http://www.tvfool.com/?option=com_wrapper&Itemid=29&q=id%3d90385971afa512 Over-the-air TV report for Port Dover, Ontario] at TV Fool</ref>\n\nAt least 4,532 individuals, or families, have their remains interred at Port Dover Cemetery on the Blue Line Road, including famous poet, novelist, short-story writer, critic and editor [[Raymond Knister]]. The cemetery is a [[United Empire Loyalist]] cemetery that includes veterans from the [[War of 1812]] along with other wars and conflicts that Canada was involved in. Due to the changing Canadian economic climate, a storage place for cremated remains was installed on the premises in 2011.<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/cemetery/2163043/port-dover-cemetery Port Dover Cemetery information] at Find a Grave</ref>\n\n[[Ride Norfolk]] offers transportation between Port Dover and Simcoe on Thursdays and Fridays. This service is used for people in Simcoe to access the tourist attractions of Port Dover mainly during the summer months. It can also be used for Port Dover residents to access doctors, medical services, and dental services in Simcoe that would usually require an automobile.\n\n===Etymology===\nFirst recorded in its Latinised form of ''[[Portus Dubris]]'', the name derives from the [[British language (Celtic)|Brythonic]] word for waters (''dwfr'' in [[Middle Welsh]]). The same element is present in the towns [[French language|French]] (Douvres) and [[Welsh Language|Modern Welsh]] (Dofr) forms.\n\n===Climate===\nBetween the years 1897 and 1977, only the winter of 1975 was considered to be a mild winter for the Port Dover area.<ref>{{cite journal | title = Maximum Freezing Degree-Days as a Winter Severity Index for the Great Lakes, 1897\u20131977 | journal = Monthly Weather Review | volume = 108 | issue = 9 | pages = 1440\u20131445 | publisher = American Meteorological Society | doi = 10.1175/1520-0493(1980)108<1440:MFDDAA>2.0.CO;2 | issn = 1520-0493 | year = 1980 | bibcode = 1980MWRv..108.1440A | last1 = Assel | first1 = Raymond A. }}</ref> From the late 1990s onwards, winters have become more mild due to Earth's changing climate. Port Dover traditionally belongs to the [[humid continental climate]] zone, even with the recent mild winters and warmer dry summers.\n\nThe warmest summers that Port Dover has witnessed occurred in 1998, 2003, 2005, 2006, 2007, 2009 (with the exception of the month of July<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.ec.gc.ca/default.asp?lang=en&n=714D9AAE-1&news=7DDF8AF2-FE36-439D-A474-4FD32F86C148| title = Ontario Weather Review - July 2009| publisher = Environment Canada| date = 2009-09-01| accessdate = 2011-10-27| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121203043636/http://www.ec.gc.ca/default.asp?lang=En&n=714D9AAE-1&news=7DDF8AF2-FE36-439D-A474-4FD32F86C148| archivedate = December 3, 2012| df = mdy-all}}</ref>), 2010, 2012, 2013, 2014, 2015 and 2016.<ref name=NOAA2015>{{cite news|url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/sotc/global/201613|title=Global Analysis - Annual 2016|publisher=NOAA|accessdate=19 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nShould the sea levels rise by {{convert|60|m|ft|disp=or}}, Port Dover would not be affected by flooding.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://flood.firetree.net/?ll=42.8780,-80.4199&z=7&m=60| title = Impact of global warming on Port Dover, Ontario | publisher = Firetree| accessdate = 2012-07-02}}</ref> However, it may be affected by droughts as a by-product of the dislocation of available fresh water and may be forced to rely on [[desalination|desalinated]] salt water piped in from the [[Eastern United States]]. Constructing the proper infrastructure to carry the water hundreds of miles away would take considerable manpower along with significant economic costs and an unprecedented level of cooperation from multiple federal, state/provincial, and municipal governments.\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Port Dover, Ontario (1961\u20131990)\n|metric first = yes\n|single line = yes\n|Jan record high C = 13.9\n|Feb record high C = 14.4\n|Mar record high C = 22.8\n|Apr record high C = 27.8\n|May record high C = 32.2\n|Jun record high C = 34.4\n|Jul record high C = 40.0\n|Aug record high C = 36.1\n|Sep record high C = 33.3\n|Oct record high C = 29.4\n|Nov record high C = 24.4\n|Dec record high C = 16.7\n|year record high C = 40.0\n|Jan high C = -2.2\n|Feb high C = -1.0\n|Mar high C = 4.2\n|Apr high C = 11.0\n|May high C = 17.8\n|Jun high C = 22.9\n|Jul high C = 25.9\n|Aug high C = 25.1\n|Sep high C = 20.9\n|Oct high C = 14.2\n|Nov high C = 7.5\n|Dec high C = 1.0\n|year high C = 12.3\n|Jan mean C = \u22125.6\n|Feb mean C = \u22124.9\n|Mar mean C = 0.3\n|Apr mean C = 6.2\n|May mean C = 12.5\n|Jun mean C = 17.8\n|Jul mean C = 20.7\n|Aug mean C = 20.1\n|Sep mean C = 16.2\n|Oct mean C = 9.9\n|Nov mean C = 4.2\n|Dec mean C = \u22122.2\n|year mean C = 7.9\n|Jan low C = -9.1\n|Feb low C = -8.9\n|Mar low C = -3.7\n|Apr low C = 1.3\n|May low C = 7.2\n|Jun low C = 12.6\n|Jul low C = 15.5\n|Aug low C = 15.0\n|Sep low C = 11.4\n|Oct low C = 5.6\n|Nov low C = 0.8\n|Dec low C = -5.4\n|year low C = 3.5\n|Jan record low C = -32.2\n|Feb record low C = -33.3\n|Mar record low C = -26.1\n|Apr record low C = -14.4\n|May record low C = -6.7\n|Jun record low C = -1.7\n|Jul record low C = 3.3\n|Aug record low C = 1.1\n|Sep record low C = -2.8\n|Oct record low C = -7.8\n|Nov record low C = -18.9\n|Dec record low C = -29.4\n|year record low C = -33.3\n|source 1 = [[Environment Canada]]<ref name= CCN>{{cite web\n| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20190819085632/http://climate.weather.gc.ca/climate_normals/results_1961_1990_e.html?searchType=stnProv&lstProvince=ON&txtCentralLatMin=0&txtCentralLatSec=0&txtCentralLongMin=0&txtCentralLongSec=0&stnID=958&dispBack=0\n| archivedate = August 19, 2019\n| url = http://climate.weather.gc.ca/climate_normals/results_1961_1990_e.html?searchType=stnProv&lstProvince=ON&txtCentralLatMin=0&txtCentralLatSec=0&txtCentralLongMin=0&txtCentralLongSec=0&stnID=958&dispBack=0\n| title = Port Dover, Ontario\n| work = Canadian Climate Normals 1961\u20131990\n| publisher = Environment Canada\n| accessdate = August 19, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===History===\n{{see also|Timeline of Port Dover, Ontario history}}\n\nPort Dover's earliest known inhabitants, from around the year 1000 until approximately 300\u2013350 years later, were the [[Algonquin people|Algonquin]] nation. They were noted flint-workers and evidence of their skill in crafting arrowheads is still to be found in open worked field areas surrounding the village. The next wave of inhabitants were the [[Neutral Nation|Attawandaron]] nation, the Neutrals, who occupied the region from about 1350 until their absorption by the [[Iroquois]] in the year 1651. The last significant native nation to occupy the area was the [[Mississaugas]].\n\nIn 1670, French missionaries [[Fran\u00e7ois Dollier de Casson]] and [[Ren\u00e9 Br\u00e9hant de Galin\u00e9e]] became the first Europeans to winter at what is now Port Dover. Earthen remains and a plaque mark the spot near the fork of the Lynn River (Patterson's Creek to many older Port Doverites) and Black Creek where they and seven Frenchmen (the first Europeans known to have ascended the Great Lakes to Sault Ste. Marie) built a hut and chapel.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wintering Site |url=http://www.ontarioplaques.com/Plaques/Plaque_Norfolk20.html |website=ontarioplaques.com |publisher=Alan L Brown |accessdate=March 12, 2019}}</ref> Just outside the community, a cross with the arms of France had been erected on 23 March 1670, claiming the area for King Louis XIV over the Lake Erie region.<ref>{{cite web |title=Cliff Site |url=http://www.ontarioplaques.com/Plaques/Plaque_Norfolk19.html |website=ontarioplaques.com |publisher=Alan L. Brown |accessdate=March 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nBy 1794 the first settlers, a group of [[United Empire Loyalists]], had established a hamlet known as Dover Mills (named for the English port of [[Dover]]). Peter Walker was the first settler of this community, becoming its unofficial founder.<ref>[http://www.ontarioplaques.com/Plaques_MNO/Plaque_Norfolk15.html ''The Founding of Port Dover''] at OntarioPlaques.com</ref>\n\nThis community was the subject of an [[Raid on Port Dover|American raid]] during the [[War of 1812]], on May 14\u201315, 1814. Much of it was destroyed but was later rebuilt.<ref>{{cite web |title=Campbell's Raid 1814 |url=http://www.ontarioplaques.com/Plaques/Plaque_Norfolk02.html |website=ontarioplaques.com |publisher=Alan L. Brown |accessdate=March 12, 2019}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite web\n| url=http://www.visit1812.com/history/\n| title=The history of the War of 1812\n| publisher=The official war of 1812 bicentennial site\n| archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query\n| archivedate=January 5, 2010\n}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite book\n| isbn=978-1-55002-626-9\n| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UmbQbOcdKngC&pg=PT81&lpg=PT81&dq=%22Port+Dover%22+Ontario+OR+%22Upper+Canada%22+raid+or+%22war+of+1812%22#v=onepage&q=%22Port%20Dover%22%20Ontario%20OR%20%22Upper%20Canada%22%20raid%20or%20%22war%20of%201812%22&f=false\n| title=Guidebook to the Historic Sites of the War of 1812\n| publisher=[[Dundurn Group|Dundurn]]\n| year=2006\n| author=Gilbert Collins\n| accessdate=January 5, 2010\n}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite news\n| url=http://www.heritagefdn.on.ca/userfiles/page_attachments/Library/1/3884445_Robert_Nichol_ENG.pdf\n| title=Robert Nichol, c. 1774-1824\n| publisher=[[Ontario Heritage Trust]]\n| date=September 24, 2009\n| archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query\n| archivedate=January 5, 2010\n}}</ref>\nAfter making their landing on the shore, 750 American soldiers launched a surprise attack on the village's civilians.<ref name=\"boatingontario\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boatingontario.ca/Articles/tabid/71/ID/40/PageID/47/Discovering-Eastern-Lake-Erie.aspx|title=Discovering Lake Erie: Port Dover and Long Point Bay|publisher=Boating Ontario}}</ref> Scattered elements of nearby militia and regular units tried to defend the village without any success. Re-enactments carried out by local volunteer groups have allowed the British-Canadian forces to soundly defeat the American troops in battle.<ref name=\"boatingontario\"/> The survivors of the war rebuilt the town of  Port Dover further downstream on Patterson's Creek. The raid was part of America's [[Niagara campaign]]s toward the end of the War of 1812.\n\nDuring the war, in August 1812, Major General [[Isaac Brock]] gathered a force of regulars and militia here. Crossing the lake by boat, they reached Amherstburg (then also in Upper Canada) and attacked and captured the American Hull's Army at Detroit.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Capture of Detroit |url=http://www.ontarioplaques.com/Plaques/Plaque_Norfolk25.html |website=ontarioplaques.com |publisher=Alan L. Brown |accessdate=March 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1835, Port Dover was incorporated as a village and later as a town.\n\nBy 1842, the village was growing and had a population of almost 400. The harbour, lighthouse and bridge across the river had been completed as had the road to Hamilton; there was a grammar school, a grist mill, a saw mill and a Presbyterian church in the course of construction.<ref name=\"norfolkofficialplan.ca\">{{cite web |title=Cultural Heritage Landscape and Built Heritage Study |date=March 1, 2007|url=http://www.norfolkofficialplan.ca/lakeshore/trc/9_Cultural_Built_Heritage.pdf |publisher=Unterman McPhail Associates|page=14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120223224044/http://www.norfolkofficialplan.ca/lakeshore/trc/9_Cultural_Built_Heritage.pdf |archive-date=February 23, 2012}}</ref> By 1896 the population was 1,000.<ref>https://books.google.com/books?id=z6wOAAAAYAAJ, page 393</ref>\n\nIn 1877, Port Dover was a large village with 1,100 residents, most living on the west bank of the River Lynn. The South Norfolk Railway was started in the county and began operating in 1889. Even earlier, the Hamilton & Lake Erie Railway (H&LER) began operating in 1873 but was merged with the Hamilton &\nNorthwestern Railway which completed the final section to Port Dover and to Jarvis in the mid 1870s.<ref name=\"norfolkofficialplan.ca\"/> A report from 1924 also discusses an electric railway that had been introduced \"in recent years\". This was the [[Grand River Railway]] that connected Hespeler, Berlin (later called Kitchener) and Waterloo with connection to Brantford and Port Dover.<ref name=\"nornet.on.ca\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nornet.on.ca/~jcardiff/transcipts/bios-photos/essays/glorious.html |title=Glorious Old Norfolk |author=Bruce M. Pearce |publisher=Norfolk Historical Society|accessdate=March 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Erie Beach, Pier and lighthouse at Port Dover, Ontario -a.jpg|left|thumb|At least during the warm months, palm trees thrive on Erie Beach, Port Dover]]\n\nBy the 1920s tourism was an important contributor to the economy, with many summer visitors attracted by the beach. There was some light industry in the town but Port Dover was best known as a major fishing centre, with fish shipped by rail and by ship not only within Canada but also to the U.S.<ref name=\"nornet.on.ca\"/> Notable amenities like Ivey's Greenhouses and the incredible Port Dover beaches caused most of the passenger train traffic to occur during the summer months.<ref name=\"lenpd\">{{cite web|url=http://www.trainweb.org/elso/len.htm|title=LAKE ERIE & NORTHERN RAILWAY|publisher=Train Web}}</ref> Rail service was also offered on the Port Dover & Lake Huron Railway (later purchased by Canadian National) line from the [[Caledonia Train Station]] to Port Dover until these services were cancelled after October 26, 1957.\n\nA popular amusement arcade was in operation in Port Dover from the mid-1950s to the mid-1990s.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=CBwEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA77&lpg=PA77&dq=port+dover+ontario+arcade&source=bl&ots=hL3RQdZPoQ&sig=G7laquwiY9IbUI90ZSyolB8hW7A&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwirltjvi93UAhWo24MKHcXqBM4Q6AEIRTAH#v=onepage&q=port%20dover%20ontario%20arcade&f=false ''Beaches Sport Coin Arcades - Juke Music] at Google Books</ref> Originally consisting of pinball games, it would expand to include video arcade games. During the late-1960s and early-1970s, local teenagers would frequently hang out at places like the Blue Pickerel, the [[ferris wheel]], and the Summer Garden where musical acts like [[Guy Lombardo]] would make frequent appearances.<ref>[http://www.pbase.com/duncanbristow/simcoe_1970 Simcoe Composite School and Norfolk County 1969-72 (Pentax SV / 50mm f1.8 lens)] at PBase</ref>\n\nBusinesses would often close one hour earlier on Wednesday as a measure to ensure that breadwinners, homemakers and their children would spend more time together until the 1970s. This occurred regardless of negative economic effects and would apply to most non-essential services.\n\nIn 1974, the town was amalgamated into the new city of [[Nanticoke, Ontario|Nanticoke]] within the Regional Municipality of Haldimand-Norfolk.\n\nThe Paris Port Dover Pipe Band was established on February 18, 2000 by [[Pipe Major]] Gordon Black as a competitive and as a community pipe band.<ref name=\"pipeband\">{{cite web|url=http://www.parisstaronline.com/ArticleDisplay.aspx?e=2710320&archive=true|title=Paris-Port Dover Pipe Band celebrates 10th anniversary|publisher=Paris Star Online}}</ref> They act as [[ambassador]]s on the global level as well as on a local level. The band was formally established when a constitution and small band were formed out of ten pipers, one bass, and one snare.<ref name=\"pipeband\"/> In 2001, Nanticoke and all other municipalities within the region were dissolved and the region was divided into two single tier municipalities. Port Dover is now an unincorporated community in Ward 6 of Norfolk County. The [[Stanley Cup]] came to Port Dover in 2004 (with [[Jassen Cullimore]]) when the [[2003\u201304 Tampa Bay Lightning season|2003\u201304 Tampa Bay Lightning]] won the Cup. He was the fourth NHL player to present the Stanley Cup to this small hockey town on the shore of Lake Erie.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hhof.com/html/exSCJ04_37.shtml|title=Stanley Cup Journals 2004: 37|publisher=[[Hockey Hall of Fame]]|accessdate=July 27, 2006|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927195903/http://www.hhof.com/html/exSCJ04_37.shtml|archivedate=September 27, 2007|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The [[Canadian Coast Guard]] stationed the [[Cape-class motor lifeboat]] [[CCGS Cape Lambton|CCGS ''Cape Lambton'']] in the community in 2005.<ref name=CcgCapeLambton2005-08-11>\n{{cite news\n| url=http://www.dfo-mpo.gc.ca/media/npress-communique/2005/ca12-eng.htm\n| title=Lloyd St. Amand Announces the Dedication of the Cape Lambton in Port Dover Ontario\n| publisher=[[Canadian Coast Guard]]\n| date=August 11, 2005\n| author=Theresa Nichols\n| archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query\n| archivedate=January 5, 2010\n}}</ref>\n\nCertain segments of the 2009 American [[horror film]] ''[[Survival of the Dead]]'' were filmed in Port Dover.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/37358/survival-dead-uncle-creepys-pictorial-diary-dead|title=Survival of the Dead: Uncle Creepy's Pictorial Diary of the Dead|publisher=DreadCentral}}</ref> The film was directed by [[George A. Romero]] and starred [[Alan van Sprang]], [[Kenneth Welsh]], and [[Kathleen Munroe]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/33735/fantastic-fest-09-romero-discusses-future-dead|title=Fantastic Fest 09: Romero Discusses the Future of the Dead|publisher=DreadCentral}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/36393/three-new-clips-george-a-romeros-survival-dead|title=Three New Clips: George A. Romero's Survival of the Dead|publisher=DreadCentral}}</ref> 40 [[wind turbine]]s were supposed to be built in the area starting in 2013.<ref name=BrantfordExpositor>\n{{cite news\n |url         = http://www.brantfordexpositor.ca/ArticleDisplay.aspx?e=2527693&archive=true\n |title       = Green projects receive go-ahead\n |publisher   = [[Brantford Expositor]]\n |year        = 2011\n |accessdate  = January 24, 2012\n |quote       = The big news, however, was in Haldimand County. That community was awarded a project that could see up to 100 wind turbines along the lake-shore in the Nanticoke area. As well, the proposal that includes the Port Dover windmills extends into Haldimand, where another 40 or more turbines could be located.\n |author      = Daniel Pearce\n |url-status     = bot: unknown\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/query\n |archivedate = January 24, 2012\n |df          = mdy-all\n}}\n\n</ref><ref name=SimcoeReformer2012-01-23>\n{{cite news\n |url         = http://www.simcoereformer.ca/ArticleDisplay.aspx?e=3445609\n |title       = Farm group calls for turbine halt\n |publisher   = [[Simcoe Reformer]]\n |date        = January 23, 2012\n |accessdate  = January 24, 2012\n |quote       = \"We are taking a look at those and we are determined to get clean, renewable energy into the province of Ontario and secure the jobs that help Ontario serve the world with green energy,\" Bentley said.\n |author      = John Miner\n |url-status     = bot: unknown\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/query\n |archivedate = January 24, 2012\n |df          = mdy-all\n}}\n\n</ref><ref>\n{{cite news\n |url         = http://www.simcoereformer.ca/ArticleDisplay.aspx?e=3189184&archive=true\n |title       = Work together to tackle wind turbine concerns\n |publisher   = [[Simcoe Reformer]]\n |date        = July 2011\n |accessdate  = January 24, 2012\n |quote       = Please be aware that Capital Power Corporation is in the process of planning to build 13 wind turbines here in the east end of Norfolk County.\n |url-status     = bot: unknown\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/query\n |archivedate = January 24, 2012\n |df          = mdy-all\n}}\n\n</ref> However, Norfolk County council has effectively banned the placement of new wind turbines due to concerns about rural spaces being completely \"industrialized\" and \"unnatural\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.simcoereformer.ca/2013/05/14/norfolk-seeks-end-to-turbine-development| title = Norfolk Seeks End to Turbine Development| accessdate = May 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\nUntil 2013, Port Dover had a [[Port Dover Composite School|high school]] which served students aged 14 through 21 in the immediate area. Approximately 1800 young people had fled the Port Dover Area between 2001 and 2011. Academic programs in [[Valley Heights Secondary School]] and [[Delhi District Secondary School]] were beefed up and prepared to accept former PDCS students after the closure date.<ref name=\"pdcswillclose\">{{cite web |title=PDCS will close at end of semester |work=The Simcoe Reformer |url=http://www.simcoereformer.ca/2012/10/15/pdcs-will-close-at-end-of-semester |accessdate=October 16, 2012}}</ref> An elementary school called '''''Lakewood Public School''''' recently opened in the old PDCS building.<ref>[http://www.granderie.ca/Community/Newsroom/Feature%20Stories/Pages/Celebrating-a-new-adventure-at-Lakewood-Elementary-.aspx ''Celebrating a new adventure at Lakewood Elementary''] at Grand Erie District School Board</ref>\n\n====Notable people====\n{{More citations needed section|date=October 2015}}\n* [[Toby Barrett]], Haldimand-Norfolk's current MPP (serving on the Legislative Assembly of Ontario for the [[Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario]])\n* [[Eddie Sargent]], former MPP (who served on the Legislative Assembly of Ontario for the [[Ontario Liberal Party]])\n* [[Rory Dodd]], rock vocalist.\n* [[Henry Laird]], journalist, wholesaler, and political figure who served Regina, Saskatchewan in the [[Senate of Canada]]\n* [[Megan Timpf]], International softball player, Olympic Athlete\n* [[Jassen Cullimore]], NHL Stanley Cup Player\n* [[John Axford]], Major League Baseball pitcher\n* [[Charles Berkeley Powell]], businessman and former member of the [[Legislative Assembly of Ontario]] (Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario)\n* [[Joey Muha]], Drummer and musician\n\n===Attractions===\nPort Dover hosts tens of thousands of people every Friday the 13th for the [[Friday the 13th motorcycle rally]], which was started on 13 November 1981 by a local bike shop owner named Chris Simons at what was then the Commercial Hotel on Main Street.<ref>Pat Brennan, [https://www.simcoereformer.ca/news/local-news/friday-the-13th-keeps-on-rolling \"Friday the 13th means thousands of bikers descending on the Lake Erie community of Port Dover\"], ''National Post'', 12 May 2016</ref><ref>Monte Sonnenberg, [https://www.simcoereformer.ca/news/local-news/friday-the-13th-keeps-on-rolling \"Friday the 13th keeps on rolling\"], ''Simcoe Reformer'', 25 January 2019</ref>\n\nPort Dover is also home to the famous ''Arbor'' hot dog restaurant and the ''Knetchel''s neighborhood market and fish restaurant.<ref name=\"travelingluck\"/> The Arbor hot dog restaurant is an inexpensive Canadian-style fast food establishment that serves soft ice cream in addition to French fries and its refreshing golden glow drink. While the value is considered to be average by local standards, the food is considered to be slightly above average. The service and the atmosphere are considered to be good by local standards. It has been a tradition for families living in Norfolk County to go to the Arbor at least once during the course of the summer months. Children enjoy the food options in addition to most of the toppings and fixings. The quickness of the service rivals that of McDonald's or Dairy Queen.<ref>[https://www.tripadvisor.ca/Restaurant_Review-g940854-d981604-Reviews-Arbor_Restaurant-Port_Dover_Norfolk_County_Ontario.html Arbor Restaurant] at Trip Advisor</ref>\n\nThe Erie Beach Hotel with its Cove Room <ref>Staff, [https://www.portdovermapleleaf.com/tony-schneider-sr-was-a-lifelong-community-builder/ \"Tony Schneider Sr was a lifelong community builder\"], ''Port Dover Maple Leaf'', April 2016</ref> and The Beach House are also popular dining attractions.\n\nThe Dover Cheese Shop is considered to be one of the top five important things to see in Port Dover. Cheese is served in very good-to-excellent quality along with crackers and it is located close to the Lighthouse Festival Theatre. Imported and Canadian cheese are sold there and the walkability of the venue allows anyone to stroll right in from the main street.<ref>[https://www.tripadvisor.ca/Attraction_Review-g940854-d6522773-Reviews-Dover_Cheese_Shop-Port_Dover_Norfolk_County_Ontario.html Dover Cheese Shop] at Trip Advisor</ref>\n\nThe Port Dover Harbour Museum is a specialty museum that deals with shipwrecks and the local fishing industry. A kids' area is included that includes a stereoscope viewer and a good number of pictures to view in it. Located on a lakeside with exhibits that interests people who are into maritime culture, there are also displays of fishing boats from years gone by. A vintage [[morse code]] machine can be viewed in the museum; morse code was used to deliver messages from ship to shore in the early days of the local fishing industry.<ref>[https://www.tripadvisor.ca/Attraction_Review-g940854-d2232978-Reviews-Port_Dover_Harbour_Museum-Port_Dover_Norfolk_County_Ontario.html Port Dover Harbour Museum] at Trip Advisor</ref>\n\nThe \"Cliff Site\" was the first place designated by the federal [[Minister of the Environment (Canada)|Minister of the Environment]] as a [[National Historic Sites of Canada|National Historic Site of Canada]] ({{lang-fr|Lieux historiques nationaux du Canada}}), as being of national historic significance. There two priests claimed sovereignty over the [[Lake Erie]] region for [[Louis XIV of France]] in 1670.<ref>{{cite book |year=1979 |title=Recognizing Canadian History: The Historic Sites and Monuments Board of Canada |publisher=Parks Canada |location=Ottawa |isbn=0-662-50533-6 |at=p. 49 |ref=History79}}</ref>\n\nLocated just a short driving distance away from the [[Stelco Lake Erie Works]] in [[Nanticoke, Ontario|Nanticoke]], Port Dover is the site of romantic sunsets along its surrounding countryside.<ref name=\"travelingluck\">[http://travelingluck.com/North%20America/Canada/Ontario/_6111731_Port%20Dover.html#local_map ''Port Dover, Ontario, Canada''] at TravelingLuck.com</ref> Port Dover can be used as an easy urban walking trail year round. Recommended activities are cycling, running, hiking, and walking. There are hills on Silver Lake Drive, Prospect Street, Bridge Street, and St. George Street. Most of the streets have sidewalks; but care should be taken around traffic especially during summer weekends. Walking on Park Street or Market Street takes the participant to Powell Park, which is the social epicenter of Port Dover. Depending on the participants' activity level, the town can be walked through in either 3 kilometres or 5 kilometres.<ref>[http://www.ontariotrails.on.ca/trails/view/port-dover-urban-trail Port Dover Urban Trail information] at Ontario Trails</ref>\n\nThere are scenic [[waterfall]]s nearby and tourists generally go to nearby Port Ryerse as a side trip.<ref name=\"travelingluck\"/> Local roads that originate from here often lead to the hamlets of Fishers Glen, Normandale and Turkey Point (which is another seasonal beach destination).<ref name=\"itcwebdesigns\"/> Even the farmers here generally enjoy the sunsets on their property.<ref name=\"travelingluck\"/> [[Apple cider|Apple wine]], produced by the local farmers themselves, can be purchased by anyone due to their lack of alcohol content.<ref name=\"itcwebdesigns\"/> This product is available in the Port Dover area.<ref name=\"itcwebdesigns\"/> On clear summer nights, the Port Dover lighthouse can be seen glimmering brightly with the moon.<ref name=\"travelingluck\"/> The beaches in Port Dover have a tendency to emulate those that are beside the [[Mediterranean Sea]].<ref name=\"itcwebdesigns\">[http://www.itcwebdesigns.com/port_dover_ca.htm ''Visit and explore Port Dover''] at ITCWebDesigns.com</ref>\n\n<gallery class=\"center\" mode=\"packed\" heights=\"165\" caption=\"Views of Port Dover, Ontario\">\nFile:Willie's in Norfolk County.jpg|alt=Willie's Restaurant in Port Dover on Friday, August 13, 2004.|Willie's Restaurant in Port Dover on Friday, August 13, 2004.\nFile:PortDoverONRailwayStationLate1930s.jpg|alt=Union Station in Port Dover, circa the late-1930s.|Union Station in Port Dover, circa the late-1930s.\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Geographic location  <!-- This geo box is for DIRECTLY ADJACENT municipalities as standardized for all other municipalities -->\n| Centre    = Port Dover\n| North     = [[Simcoe, Ontario|Simcoe]]\n| Northeast = [[Jarvis, Ontario|Jarvis]]\n| East      = [[Nanticoke, Ontario|Nanticoke]]\n| Southeast = [[Lake Erie]]\n| South     = Lake Erie\n| Southwest = Port Ryerse\n| West      = \n| Northwest = [[Walsh, Ontario|Walsh]]\n}}\n\n{{Norfolk County, Ontario}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Communities in Norfolk County, Ontario]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1794]]\n[[Category:1794 establishments in the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Populated places on Lake Erie in Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2015}}\n\n{{short description|Community of Norfolk County, Ontario, Canada}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Port Dover, Ontario\n|settlement_type        = Unincorporated hamlet in Norfolk County\n|other_name             =\n|native_name            =  <!-- for cities whose native name is not in English -->\n|nickname               =\n|motto                  = \n|image_skyline          = Boats moored at Port Dover, Ontario.jpg|frameless|upright=1.15\n|imagesize              =\n|image_caption          = Boats moored at Port Dover, Ontario.\n|image_flag             =\n|flag_size              =\n|image_seal             =\n|seal_size              =\n|image_shield           =\n|shield_size            =\n|image_blank_emblem     =\n|blank_emblem_size      =\n|image_map              =\n|mapsize                =\n|map_caption            =\n|image_map1             =\n|mapsize1               =\n|map_caption1           =\n|image_dot_map          =\n|dot_mapsize            =\n|dot_map_caption        =\n|dot_x =  |dot_y =\n|pushpin_map            = Canada Southern Ontario\n|pushpin_label_position =\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location in southern Ontario\n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = {{CAN}}\n|subdivision_type1      = [[List of Canadian Provinces|Province]]\n|subdivision_name1      = {{ON}}\n|subdivision_name3      =\n|subdivision_type4      =\n|subdivision_name4      =\n|government_type        =\n|leader_title           = Mayor\n|leader_name            = Kristal Chopp\n|leader_title1          = Governing Body\n|leader_name1           = The Council of The Corporation of Norfolk County\n|leader_title2          = [[House of Commons of Canada|MPs]]\n|leader_name2           = [[Diane Finley]] ([[Conservative Party of Canada|Con]])\n|leader_title3          = [[Legislative Assembly|MPPs]]\n|leader_name3           = [[Toby Barrett]] ([[Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario|PC]])\n|leader_title4          =\n|leader_name4           =\n|established_title      = Established\n|established_date       = 1794 as Dover Mills\n|established_title2     = \n|established_date2      = 1974 (Regional Municipality of Haldimand-Norfolk)\n|established_title3     = Amalgamated into Norfolk County\n|established_date3      = 2001 (Single-tier municipality)\n|area_magnitude         =\n|unit_pref              = <!--Enter: Imperial, if Imperial (metric) is desired-->\n|area_footnotes         = \n|area_total_km2         =\n|area_land_km2          = 9.15\n|area_water_km2         =\n|area_water_percent     =\n|population             = 6161\n|population_as_of       = 2016\n|population_density_km2 = 698.04\n|timezone               = [[North American Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n|utc_offset             = -5\n|timezone_DST           = [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]]\n|utc_offset_DST         = -4\n|coordinates            = {{coord|42|47|12|N|80|12|11|W|region:CA-ON|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_footnotes    =  <!--for references: use <ref> </ref> tags-->\n|elevation_m            = 210\n|postal_code_type       = [[Canadian postal code#Forward sortation areas|Forward sortation area]]\n|postal_code            = [[List of N postal codes of Canada|N0A]]\n|area_code              = [[Area code 519|519]] / [[Area code 226|226]] / \n|website                = [http://www.norfolkcounty.ca/ www.norfolkcounty.ca]\n|footnotes              =\n}}\n{{commons category|Port Dover, Ontario}}\n\n'''Port Dover''' is an unincorporated community and former [[town]] located in [[Norfolk County, Ontario|Norfolk County]], [[Ontario]], Canada on the north shore of [[Lake Erie]].\n\n==Summary==\nPrior to the [[War of 1812]], this community was known as '''Dover Mills'''. This community is the southern terminus for [[Ontario Highway 6]]; located {{convert|480|km|mi|disp=or}} to the south of the Northern Ontario community of [[Baldwin, Ontario|McKerrow]].<ref>{{cite map\n|title     = Road Atlas \u2013 Canada, United States, and Mexico\n|publisher = Peter Heiler Ltd\n|edition   = 2008\n|page      = 17, 19\n|section   = B6\u2013G7, G8\u2013K8, L9, M10\u2013R11}}</ref> This highway stretches northward as a two-lane, undivided highway until the traffic flow increases to four lanes shortly after it departs from [[Caledonia, Ontario|Caledonia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onthighways.com/highway_6_page_1.htm|title=Highway 6 Information for Norfolk County to City of Hamilton|work=Ontario King's Highways|accessdate=July 3, 2007}}</ref> In addition to allowing Port Dover residents direct access to the city of [[Hamilton, Ontario|Hamilton]], it also briefly merges with [[Ontario Highway 403|Highway 403]] to allow for access to the [[Royal Botanical Gardens (Ontario)|Royal Botanical Gardens]] and locations on to Toronto.\n\nThe [[postal code|postal]] [[forward sortation area]] is ''N0A''; sharing its [[Canada Post]] service with the western portion of Haldimand County. All residences and businesses within the Port Dover area have a ''583'' in their phone number.\n\nA verified amount of at least 128 species of bird have been discovered in Port Dover from 1956 to 2019; including the [[Indigo Bunting]], the [[Rose-breasted Grosbeak]], and the [[Scarlet Tanager]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://ebird.org/hotspot/L633655?m=&yr=all&changeDate=Set| title = Bird Counts in Port Dover, Ontario | publisher = eBird | date = | accessdate = 2019-05-22}}</ref>\n\nThe second largest of the [[Communities in Norfolk County, Ontario]], Port Dover had a population of 6,161 at the time of the 2016 Census.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=POPC&Code1=0658&Geo2=PR&Code2=47&Data=Count&SearchText=Port%20Dover&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1 |title=Census Profile, 2016 Census Port Dover |publisher=[[Statistics Canada]]|accessdate=March 12, 2019}}</ref> English is spoken by the majority of the residents; with 285 people speaking languages other than English or French. The majority of Port Dover residents were born in Canada, with 515 residents being born in Europe in addition to 10 African-born residents, 70 US-born residents and 70 residents who were born in Asia.<ref>[http://www.citypopulation.de/php/canada-ua-ontario.php?cityid=UA0658 Demographics information] at City Population</ref>\n\nMost people get their television either through [[Shaw Direct]], [[Bell TV]] or [[terrestrial television|over-the-air]]. There is only one channel can be picked up reliably using an outdoor antenna while an additional five channels can be picked up semi-reliably. There are twelve channels that can be picked up over-the-air only during sunny days where clouds are absent.<ref>[http://www.tvfool.com/?option=com_wrapper&Itemid=29&q=id%3d90385971afa512 Over-the-air TV report for Port Dover, Ontario] at TV Fool</ref>\n\nAt least 4,532 individuals, or families, have their remains interred at Port Dover Cemetery on the Blue Line Road, including famous poet, novelist, short-story writer, critic and editor [[Raymond Knister]]. The cemetery is a [[United Empire Loyalist]] cemetery that includes veterans from the [[War of 1812]] along with other wars and conflicts that Canada was involved in. Due to the changing Canadian economic climate, a storage place for cremated remains was installed on the premises in 2011.<ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/cemetery/2163043/port-dover-cemetery Port Dover Cemetery information] at Find a Grave</ref>\n\n[[Ride Norfolk]] offers transportation between Port Dover and Simcoe on Thursdays and Fridays. This service is used for people in Simcoe to access the tourist attractions of Port Dover mainly during the summer months. It can also be used for Port Dover residents to access doctors, medical services, and dental services in Simcoe that would usually require an automobile.\n\n===Etymology===\nFirst recorded in its Latinised form of ''[[Portus Dubris]]'', the name derives from the [[British language (Celtic)|Brythonic]] word for waters (''dwfr'' in [[Middle Welsh]]). The same element is present in the towns [[French language|French]] (Douvres) and [[Welsh Language|Modern Welsh]] (Dofr) forms.\n\n===Climate===\nBetween the years 1897 and 1977, only the winter of 1975 was considered to be a mild winter for the Port Dover area.<ref>{{cite journal | title = Maximum Freezing Degree-Days as a Winter Severity Index for the Great Lakes, 1897\u20131977 | journal = Monthly Weather Review | volume = 108 | issue = 9 | pages = 1440\u20131445 | publisher = American Meteorological Society | doi = 10.1175/1520-0493(1980)108<1440:MFDDAA>2.0.CO;2 | issn = 1520-0493 | year = 1980 | bibcode = 1980MWRv..108.1440A | last1 = Assel | first1 = Raymond A. }}</ref> From the late 1990s onwards, winters have become more mild due to Earth's changing climate. Port Dover traditionally belongs to the [[humid continental climate]] zone, even with the recent mild winters and warmer dry summers.\n\nThe warmest summers that Port Dover has witnessed occurred in 1998, 2003, 2005, 2006, 2007, 2009 (with the exception of the month of July<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.ec.gc.ca/default.asp?lang=en&n=714D9AAE-1&news=7DDF8AF2-FE36-439D-A474-4FD32F86C148| title = Ontario Weather Review - July 2009| publisher = Environment Canada| date = 2009-09-01| accessdate = 2011-10-27| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20121203043636/http://www.ec.gc.ca/default.asp?lang=En&n=714D9AAE-1&news=7DDF8AF2-FE36-439D-A474-4FD32F86C148| archivedate = December 3, 2012| df = mdy-all}}</ref>), 2010, 2012, 2013, 2014, 2015 and 2016.<ref name=NOAA2015>{{cite news|url=https://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/sotc/global/201613|title=Global Analysis - Annual 2016|publisher=NOAA|accessdate=19 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nShould the sea levels rise by {{convert|60|m|ft|disp=or}}, Port Dover would not be affected by flooding.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://flood.firetree.net/?ll=42.8780,-80.4199&z=7&m=60| title = Impact of global warming on Port Dover, Ontario | publisher = Firetree| accessdate = 2012-07-02}}</ref> However, it may be affected by droughts as a by-product of the dislocation of available fresh water and may be forced to rely on [[desalination|desalinated]] salt water piped in from the [[Eastern United States]]. Constructing the proper infrastructure to carry the water hundreds of miles away would take considerable manpower along with significant economic costs and an unprecedented level of cooperation from multiple federal, state/provincial, and municipal governments.\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Port Dover, Ontario (1961\u20131990)\n|metric first = yes\n|single line = yes\n|Jan record high C = 13.9\n|Feb record high C = 14.4\n|Mar record high C = 22.8\n|Apr record high C = 27.8\n|May record high C = 32.2\n|Jun record high C = 34.4\n|Jul record high C = 40.0\n|Aug record high C = 36.1\n|Sep record high C = 33.3\n|Oct record high C = 29.4\n|Nov record high C = 24.4\n|Dec record high C = 16.7\n|year record high C = 40.0\n|Jan high C = -2.2\n|Feb high C = -1.0\n|Mar high C = 4.2\n|Apr high C = 11.0\n|May high C = 17.8\n|Jun high C = 22.9\n|Jul high C = 25.9\n|Aug high C = 25.1\n|Sep high C = 20.9\n|Oct high C = 14.2\n|Nov high C = 7.5\n|Dec high C = 1.0\n|year high C = 12.3\n|Jan mean C = \u22125.6\n|Feb mean C = \u22124.9\n|Mar mean C = 0.3\n|Apr mean C = 6.2\n|May mean C = 12.5\n|Jun mean C = 17.8\n|Jul mean C = 20.7\n|Aug mean C = 20.1\n|Sep mean C = 16.2\n|Oct mean C = 9.9\n|Nov mean C = 4.2\n|Dec mean C = \u22122.2\n|year mean C = 7.9\n|Jan low C = -9.1\n|Feb low C = -8.9\n|Mar low C = -3.7\n|Apr low C = 1.3\n|May low C = 7.2\n|Jun low C = 12.6\n|Jul low C = 15.5\n|Aug low C = 15.0\n|Sep low C = 11.4\n|Oct low C = 5.6\n|Nov low C = 0.8\n|Dec low C = -5.4\n|year low C = 3.5\n|Jan record low C = -32.2\n|Feb record low C = -33.3\n|Mar record low C = -26.1\n|Apr record low C = -14.4\n|May record low C = -6.7\n|Jun record low C = -1.7\n|Jul record low C = 3.3\n|Aug record low C = 1.1\n|Sep record low C = -2.8\n|Oct record low C = -7.8\n|Nov record low C = -18.9\n|Dec record low C = -29.4\n|year record low C = -33.3\n|source 1 = [[Environment Canada]]<ref name= CCN>{{cite web\n| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20190819085632/http://climate.weather.gc.ca/climate_normals/results_1961_1990_e.html?searchType=stnProv&lstProvince=ON&txtCentralLatMin=0&txtCentralLatSec=0&txtCentralLongMin=0&txtCentralLongSec=0&stnID=958&dispBack=0\n| archivedate = August 19, 2019\n| url = http://climate.weather.gc.ca/climate_normals/results_1961_1990_e.html?searchType=stnProv&lstProvince=ON&txtCentralLatMin=0&txtCentralLatSec=0&txtCentralLongMin=0&txtCentralLongSec=0&stnID=958&dispBack=0\n| title = Port Dover, Ontario\n| work = Canadian Climate Normals 1961\u20131990\n| publisher = Environment Canada\n| accessdate = August 19, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===History===\n{{see also|Timeline of Port Dover, Ontario history}}\n\nPort Dover's earliest known inhabitants, from around the year 1000 until approximately 300\u2013350 years later, were the [[Algonquin people|Algonquin]] nation. They were noted flint-workers and evidence of their skill in crafting arrowheads is still to be found in open worked field areas surrounding the village. The next wave of inhabitants were the [[Neutral Nation|Attawandaron]] nation, the Neutrals, who occupied the region from about 1350 until their absorption by the [[Iroquois]] in the year 1651. The last significant native nation to occupy the area was the [[Mississaugas]].\n\nIn 1670, French missionaries [[Fran\u00e7ois Dollier de Casson]] and [[Ren\u00e9 Br\u00e9hant de Galin\u00e9e]] became the first Europeans to winter at what is now Port Dover. Earthen remains and a plaque mark the spot near the fork of the Lynn River (Patterson's Creek to many older Port Doverites) and Black Creek where they and seven Frenchmen (the first Europeans known to have ascended the Great Lakes to Sault Ste. Marie) built a hut and chapel.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wintering Site |url=http://www.ontarioplaques.com/Plaques/Plaque_Norfolk20.html |website=ontarioplaques.com |publisher=Alan L Brown |accessdate=March 12, 2019}}</ref> Just outside the community, a cross with the arms of France had been erected on 23 March 1670, claiming the area for King Louis XIV over the Lake Erie region.<ref>{{cite web |title=Cliff Site |url=http://www.ontarioplaques.com/Plaques/Plaque_Norfolk19.html |website=ontarioplaques.com |publisher=Alan L. Brown |accessdate=March 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nBy 1794 the first settlers, a group of [[United Empire Loyalists]], had established a hamlet known as Dover Mills (named for the English port of [[Dover]]). Peter Walker was the first settler of this community, becoming its unofficial founder.<ref>[http://www.ontarioplaques.com/Plaques_MNO/Plaque_Norfolk15.html ''The Founding of Port Dover''] at OntarioPlaques.com</ref>\n\nThis community was the subject of an [[Raid on Port Dover|American raid]] during the [[War of 1812]], on May 14\u201315, 1814. Much of it was destroyed but was later rebuilt.<ref>{{cite web |title=Campbell's Raid 1814 |url=http://www.ontarioplaques.com/Plaques/Plaque_Norfolk02.html |website=ontarioplaques.com |publisher=Alan L. Brown |accessdate=March 12, 2019}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite web\n| url=http://www.visit1812.com/history/\n| title=The history of the War of 1812\n| publisher=The official war of 1812 bicentennial site\n| archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query\n| archivedate=January 5, 2010\n}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite book\n| isbn=978-1-55002-626-9\n| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UmbQbOcdKngC&pg=PT81&lpg=PT81&dq=%22Port+Dover%22+Ontario+OR+%22Upper+Canada%22+raid+or+%22war+of+1812%22#v=onepage&q=%22Port%20Dover%22%20Ontario%20OR%20%22Upper%20Canada%22%20raid%20or%20%22war%20of%201812%22&f=false\n| title=Guidebook to the Historic Sites of the War of 1812\n| publisher=[[Dundurn Group|Dundurn]]\n| year=2006\n| author=Gilbert Collins\n| accessdate=January 5, 2010\n}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite news\n| url=http://www.heritagefdn.on.ca/userfiles/page_attachments/Library/1/3884445_Robert_Nichol_ENG.pdf\n| title=Robert Nichol, c. 1774-1824\n| publisher=[[Ontario Heritage Trust]]\n| date=September 24, 2009\n| archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query\n| archivedate=January 5, 2010\n}}</ref>\nAfter making their landing on the shore, 750 American soldiers launched a surprise attack on the village's civilians.<ref name=\"boatingontario\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boatingontario.ca/Articles/tabid/71/ID/40/PageID/47/Discovering-Eastern-Lake-Erie.aspx|title=Discovering Lake Erie: Port Dover and Long Point Bay|publisher=Boating Ontario}}</ref> Scattered elements of nearby militia and regular units tried to defend the village without any success. Re-enactments carried out by local volunteer groups have allowed the British-Canadian forces to soundly defeat the American troops in battle.<ref name=\"boatingontario\"/> The survivors of the war rebuilt the town of  Port Dover further downstream on Patterson's Creek. The raid was part of America's [[Niagara campaign]]s toward the end of the War of 1812.\n\nDuring the war, in August 1812, Major General [[Isaac Brock]] gathered a force of regulars and militia here. Crossing the lake by boat, they reached Amherstburg (then also in Upper Canada) and attacked and captured the American Hull's Army at Detroit.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Capture of Detroit |url=http://www.ontarioplaques.com/Plaques/Plaque_Norfolk25.html |website=ontarioplaques.com |publisher=Alan L. Brown |accessdate=March 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1835, Port Dover was incorporated as a village and later as a town.\n\nBy 1842, the village was growing and had a population of almost 400. The harbour, lighthouse and bridge across the river had been completed as had the road to Hamilton; there was a grammar school, a grist mill, a saw mill and a Presbyterian church in the course of construction.<ref name=\"norfolkofficialplan.ca\">{{cite web |title=Cultural Heritage Landscape and Built Heritage Study |date=March 1, 2007|url=http://www.norfolkofficialplan.ca/lakeshore/trc/9_Cultural_Built_Heritage.pdf |publisher=Unterman McPhail Associates|page=14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120223224044/http://www.norfolkofficialplan.ca/lakeshore/trc/9_Cultural_Built_Heritage.pdf |archive-date=February 23, 2012}}</ref> By 1896 the population was 1,000.<ref>https://books.google.com/books?id=z6wOAAAAYAAJ, page 393</ref>\n\nIn 1877, Port Dover was a large village with 1,100 residents, most living on the west bank of the River Lynn. The South Norfolk Railway was started in the county and began operating in 1889. Even earlier, the Hamilton & Lake Erie Railway (H&LER) began operating in 1873 but was merged with the Hamilton &\nNorthwestern Railway which completed the final section to Port Dover and to Jarvis in the mid 1870s.<ref name=\"norfolkofficialplan.ca\"/> A report from 1924 also discusses an electric railway that had been introduced \"in recent years\". This was the [[Grand River Railway]] that connected Hespeler, Berlin (later called Kitchener) and Waterloo with connection to Brantford and Port Dover.<ref name=\"nornet.on.ca\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nornet.on.ca/~jcardiff/transcipts/bios-photos/essays/glorious.html |title=Glorious Old Norfolk |author=Bruce M. Pearce |publisher=Norfolk Historical Society|accessdate=March 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Erie Beach, Pier and lighthouse at Port Dover, Ontario -a.jpg|left|thumb|At least during the warm months, palm trees thrive on Erie Beach, Port Dover]]\n\nBy the 1920s tourism was an important contributor to the economy, with many summer visitors attracted by the beach. There was some light industry in the town but Port Dover was best known as a major fishing centre, with fish shipped by rail and by ship not only within Canada but also to the U.S.<ref name=\"nornet.on.ca\"/> Notable amenities like Ivey's Greenhouses and the incredible Port Dover beaches caused most of the passenger train traffic to occur during the summer months.<ref name=\"lenpd\">{{cite web|url=http://www.trainweb.org/elso/len.htm|title=LAKE ERIE & NORTHERN RAILWAY|publisher=Train Web}}</ref> Rail service was also offered on the Port Dover & Lake Huron Railway (later purchased by Canadian National) line from the [[Caledonia Train Station]] to Port Dover until these services were cancelled after October 26, 1957.\n\nA popular amusement arcade was in operation in Port Dover from the mid-1950s to the mid-1990s.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=CBwEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA77&lpg=PA77&dq=port+dover+ontario+arcade&source=bl&ots=hL3RQdZPoQ&sig=G7laquwiY9IbUI90ZSyolB8hW7A&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwirltjvi93UAhWo24MKHcXqBM4Q6AEIRTAH#v=onepage&q=port%20dover%20ontario%20arcade&f=false ''Beaches Sport Coin Arcades - Juke Music] at Google Books</ref> Originally consisting of pinball games, it would expand to include video arcade games. During the late-1960s and early-1970s, local teenagers would frequently hang out at places like the Blue Pickerel, the [[ferris wheel]], and the Summer Garden where musical acts like [[Guy Lombardo]] would make frequent appearances.<ref>[http://www.pbase.com/duncanbristow/simcoe_1970 Simcoe Composite School and Norfolk County 1969-72 (Pentax SV / 50mm f1.8 lens)] at PBase</ref>\n\nBusinesses would often close one hour earlier on Wednesday as a measure to ensure that breadwinners, homemakers and their children would spend more time together until the 1970s. This occurred regardless of negative economic effects and would apply to most non-essential services.\n\nIn 1974, the town was amalgamated into the new city of [[Nanticoke, Ontario|Nanticoke]] within the Regional Municipality of Haldimand-Norfolk.\n\nThe [[Paris Port Dover Pipe Band]] was established on February 18, 2000 by [[Pipe Major]] Gordon Black as a competitive and as a community pipe band.<ref name=\"pipeband\">{{cite web|url=http://www.parisstaronline.com/ArticleDisplay.aspx?e=2710320&archive=true|title=Paris-Port Dover Pipe Band celebrates 10th anniversary|publisher=Paris Star Online}}</ref> They act as [[ambassador]]s on the global level as well as on a local level. The band was formally established when a constitution and small band were formed out of ten pipers, one bass, and one snare.<ref name=\"pipeband\"/> In 2001, Nanticoke and all other municipalities within the region were dissolved and the region was divided into two single tier municipalities. Port Dover is now an unincorporated community in Ward 6 of Norfolk County. The [[Stanley Cup]] came to Port Dover in 2004 (with [[Jassen Cullimore]]) when the [[2003\u201304 Tampa Bay Lightning season|2003\u201304 Tampa Bay Lightning]] won the Cup. He was the fourth NHL player to present the Stanley Cup to this small hockey town on the shore of Lake Erie.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hhof.com/html/exSCJ04_37.shtml|title=Stanley Cup Journals 2004: 37|publisher=[[Hockey Hall of Fame]]|accessdate=July 27, 2006|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927195903/http://www.hhof.com/html/exSCJ04_37.shtml|archivedate=September 27, 2007|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The [[Canadian Coast Guard]] stationed the [[Cape-class motor lifeboat]] [[CCGS Cape Lambton|CCGS ''Cape Lambton'']] in the community in 2005.<ref name=CcgCapeLambton2005-08-11>\n{{cite news\n| url=http://www.dfo-mpo.gc.ca/media/npress-communique/2005/ca12-eng.htm\n| title=Lloyd St. Amand Announces the Dedication of the Cape Lambton in Port Dover Ontario\n| publisher=[[Canadian Coast Guard]]\n| date=August 11, 2005\n| author=Theresa Nichols\n| archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query\n| archivedate=January 5, 2010\n}}</ref>\n\nCertain segments of the 2009 American [[horror film]] ''[[Survival of the Dead]]'' were filmed in Port Dover.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/37358/survival-dead-uncle-creepys-pictorial-diary-dead|title=Survival of the Dead: Uncle Creepy's Pictorial Diary of the Dead|publisher=DreadCentral}}</ref> The film was directed by [[George A. Romero]] and starred [[Alan van Sprang]], [[Kenneth Welsh]], and [[Kathleen Munroe]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/33735/fantastic-fest-09-romero-discusses-future-dead|title=Fantastic Fest 09: Romero Discusses the Future of the Dead|publisher=DreadCentral}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/36393/three-new-clips-george-a-romeros-survival-dead|title=Three New Clips: George A. Romero's Survival of the Dead|publisher=DreadCentral}}</ref> 40 [[wind turbine]]s were supposed to be built in the area starting in 2013.<ref name=BrantfordExpositor>\n{{cite news\n |url         = http://www.brantfordexpositor.ca/ArticleDisplay.aspx?e=2527693&archive=true\n |title       = Green projects receive go-ahead\n |publisher   = [[Brantford Expositor]]\n |year        = 2011\n |accessdate  = January 24, 2012\n |quote       = The big news, however, was in Haldimand County. That community was awarded a project that could see up to 100 wind turbines along the lake-shore in the Nanticoke area. As well, the proposal that includes the Port Dover windmills extends into Haldimand, where another 40 or more turbines could be located.\n |author      = Daniel Pearce\n |url-status     = bot: unknown\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/query\n |archivedate = January 24, 2012\n |df          = mdy-all\n}}\n\n</ref><ref name=SimcoeReformer2012-01-23>\n{{cite news\n |url         = http://www.simcoereformer.ca/ArticleDisplay.aspx?e=3445609\n |title       = Farm group calls for turbine halt\n |publisher   = [[Simcoe Reformer]]\n |date        = January 23, 2012\n |accessdate  = January 24, 2012\n |quote       = \"We are taking a look at those and we are determined to get clean, renewable energy into the province of Ontario and secure the jobs that help Ontario serve the world with green energy,\" Bentley said.\n |author      = John Miner\n |url-status     = bot: unknown\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/query\n |archivedate = January 24, 2012\n |df          = mdy-all\n}}\n\n</ref><ref>\n{{cite news\n |url         = http://www.simcoereformer.ca/ArticleDisplay.aspx?e=3189184&archive=true\n |title       = Work together to tackle wind turbine concerns\n |publisher   = [[Simcoe Reformer]]\n |date        = July 2011\n |accessdate  = January 24, 2012\n |quote       = Please be aware that Capital Power Corporation is in the process of planning to build 13 wind turbines here in the east end of Norfolk County.\n |url-status     = bot: unknown\n |archiveurl  = https://www.webcitation.org/query\n |archivedate = January 24, 2012\n |df          = mdy-all\n}}\n\n</ref> However, Norfolk County council has effectively banned the placement of new wind turbines due to concerns about rural spaces being completely \"industrialized\" and \"unnatural\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.simcoereformer.ca/2013/05/14/norfolk-seeks-end-to-turbine-development| title = Norfolk Seeks End to Turbine Development| accessdate = May 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\nUntil 2013, Port Dover had a [[Port Dover Composite School|high school]] which served students aged 14 through 21 in the immediate area. Approximately 1800 young people had fled the Port Dover Area between 2001 and 2011. Academic programs in [[Valley Heights Secondary School]] and [[Delhi District Secondary School]] were beefed up and prepared to accept former PDCS students after the closure date.<ref name=\"pdcswillclose\">{{cite web |title=PDCS will close at end of semester |work=The Simcoe Reformer |url=http://www.simcoereformer.ca/2012/10/15/pdcs-will-close-at-end-of-semester |accessdate=October 16, 2012}}</ref> An elementary school called '''''Lakewood Public School''''' recently opened in the old PDCS building.<ref>[http://www.granderie.ca/Community/Newsroom/Feature%20Stories/Pages/Celebrating-a-new-adventure-at-Lakewood-Elementary-.aspx ''Celebrating a new adventure at Lakewood Elementary''] at Grand Erie District School Board</ref>\n\n====Notable people====\n{{More citations needed section|date=October 2015}}\n* [[Toby Barrett]], Haldimand-Norfolk's current MPP (serving on the Legislative Assembly of Ontario for the [[Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario]])\n* [[Eddie Sargent]], former MPP (who served on the Legislative Assembly of Ontario for the [[Ontario Liberal Party]])\n* [[Rory Dodd]], rock vocalist.\n* [[Henry Laird]], journalist, wholesaler, and political figure who served Regina, Saskatchewan in the [[Senate of Canada]]\n* [[Megan Timpf]], International softball player, Olympic Athlete\n* [[Jassen Cullimore]], NHL Stanley Cup Player\n* [[John Axford]], Major League Baseball pitcher\n* [[Charles Berkeley Powell]], businessman and former member of the [[Legislative Assembly of Ontario]] (Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario)\n* [[Joey Muha]], Drummer and musician\n\n===Attractions===\nPort Dover hosts tens of thousands of people every Friday the 13th for the [[Friday the 13th motorcycle rally]], which was started on 13 November 1981 by a local bike shop owner named Chris Simons at what was then the Commercial Hotel on Main Street.<ref>Pat Brennan, [https://www.simcoereformer.ca/news/local-news/friday-the-13th-keeps-on-rolling \"Friday the 13th means thousands of bikers descending on the Lake Erie community of Port Dover\"], ''National Post'', 12 May 2016</ref><ref>Monte Sonnenberg, [https://www.simcoereformer.ca/news/local-news/friday-the-13th-keeps-on-rolling \"Friday the 13th keeps on rolling\"], ''Simcoe Reformer'', 25 January 2019</ref>\n\nPort Dover is also home to the famous ''Arbor'' hot dog restaurant and the ''Knetchel''s neighborhood market and fish restaurant.<ref name=\"travelingluck\"/> The Arbor hot dog restaurant is an inexpensive Canadian-style fast food establishment that serves soft ice cream in addition to French fries and its refreshing golden glow drink. While the value is considered to be average by local standards, the food is considered to be slightly above average. The service and the atmosphere are considered to be good by local standards. It has been a tradition for families living in Norfolk County to go to the Arbor at least once during the course of the summer months. Children enjoy the food options in addition to most of the toppings and fixings. The quickness of the service rivals that of McDonald's or Dairy Queen.<ref>[https://www.tripadvisor.ca/Restaurant_Review-g940854-d981604-Reviews-Arbor_Restaurant-Port_Dover_Norfolk_County_Ontario.html Arbor Restaurant] at Trip Advisor</ref>\n\nThe Erie Beach Hotel with its Cove Room <ref>Staff, [https://www.portdovermapleleaf.com/tony-schneider-sr-was-a-lifelong-community-builder/ \"Tony Schneider Sr was a lifelong community builder\"], ''Port Dover Maple Leaf'', April 2016</ref> and The Beach House are also popular dining attractions.\n\nThe Dover Cheese Shop is considered to be one of the top five important things to see in Port Dover. Cheese is served in very good-to-excellent quality along with crackers and it is located close to the Lighthouse Festival Theatre. Imported and Canadian cheese are sold there and the walkability of the venue allows anyone to stroll right in from the main street.<ref>[https://www.tripadvisor.ca/Attraction_Review-g940854-d6522773-Reviews-Dover_Cheese_Shop-Port_Dover_Norfolk_County_Ontario.html Dover Cheese Shop] at Trip Advisor</ref>\n\nThe Port Dover Harbour Museum is a specialty museum that deals with shipwrecks and the local fishing industry. A kids' area is included that includes a stereoscope viewer and a good number of pictures to view in it. Located on a lakeside with exhibits that interests people who are into maritime culture, there are also displays of fishing boats from years gone by. A vintage [[morse code]] machine can be viewed in the museum; morse code was used to deliver messages from ship to shore in the early days of the local fishing industry.<ref>[https://www.tripadvisor.ca/Attraction_Review-g940854-d2232978-Reviews-Port_Dover_Harbour_Museum-Port_Dover_Norfolk_County_Ontario.html Port Dover Harbour Museum] at Trip Advisor</ref>\n\nThe \"Cliff Site\" was the first place designated by the federal [[Minister of the Environment (Canada)|Minister of the Environment]] as a [[National Historic Sites of Canada|National Historic Site of Canada]] ({{lang-fr|Lieux historiques nationaux du Canada}}), as being of national historic significance. There two priests claimed sovereignty over the [[Lake Erie]] region for [[Louis XIV of France]] in 1670.<ref>{{cite book |year=1979 |title=Recognizing Canadian History: The Historic Sites and Monuments Board of Canada |publisher=Parks Canada |location=Ottawa |isbn=0-662-50533-6 |at=p. 49 |ref=History79}}</ref>\n\nLocated just a short driving distance away from the [[Stelco Lake Erie Works]] in [[Nanticoke, Ontario|Nanticoke]], Port Dover is the site of romantic sunsets along its surrounding countryside.<ref name=\"travelingluck\">[http://travelingluck.com/North%20America/Canada/Ontario/_6111731_Port%20Dover.html#local_map ''Port Dover, Ontario, Canada''] at TravelingLuck.com</ref> Port Dover can be used as an easy urban walking trail year round. Recommended activities are cycling, running, hiking, and walking. There are hills on Silver Lake Drive, Prospect Street, Bridge Street, and St. George Street. Most of the streets have sidewalks; but care should be taken around traffic especially during summer weekends. Walking on Park Street or Market Street takes the participant to Powell Park, which is the social epicenter of Port Dover. Depending on the participants' activity level, the town can be walked through in either 3 kilometres or 5 kilometres.<ref>[http://www.ontariotrails.on.ca/trails/view/port-dover-urban-trail Port Dover Urban Trail information] at Ontario Trails</ref>\n\nThere are scenic [[waterfall]]s nearby and tourists generally go to nearby Port Ryerse as a side trip.<ref name=\"travelingluck\"/> Local roads that originate from here often lead to the hamlets of Fishers Glen, Normandale and Turkey Point (which is another seasonal beach destination).<ref name=\"itcwebdesigns\"/> Even the farmers here generally enjoy the sunsets on their property.<ref name=\"travelingluck\"/> [[Apple cider|Apple wine]], produced by the local farmers themselves, can be purchased by anyone due to their lack of alcohol content.<ref name=\"itcwebdesigns\"/> This product is available in the Port Dover area.<ref name=\"itcwebdesigns\"/> On clear summer nights, the Port Dover lighthouse can be seen glimmering brightly with the moon.<ref name=\"travelingluck\"/> The beaches in Port Dover have a tendency to emulate those that are beside the [[Mediterranean Sea]].<ref name=\"itcwebdesigns\">[http://www.itcwebdesigns.com/port_dover_ca.htm ''Visit and explore Port Dover''] at ITCWebDesigns.com</ref>\n\n<gallery class=\"center\" mode=\"packed\" heights=\"165\" caption=\"Views of Port Dover, Ontario\">\nFile:Willie's in Norfolk County.jpg|alt=Willie's Restaurant in Port Dover on Friday, August 13, 2004.|Willie's Restaurant in Port Dover on Friday, August 13, 2004.\nFile:PortDoverONRailwayStationLate1930s.jpg|alt=Union Station in Port Dover, circa the late-1930s.|Union Station in Port Dover, circa the late-1930s.\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Geographic location  <!-- This geo box is for DIRECTLY ADJACENT municipalities as standardized for all other municipalities -->\n| Centre    = Port Dover\n| North     = [[Simcoe, Ontario|Simcoe]]\n| Northeast = [[Jarvis, Ontario|Jarvis]]\n| East      = [[Nanticoke, Ontario|Nanticoke]]\n| Southeast = [[Lake Erie]]\n| South     = Lake Erie\n| Southwest = Port Ryerse\n| West      = \n| Northwest = [[Walsh, Ontario|Walsh]]\n}}\n\n{{Norfolk County, Ontario}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Communities in Norfolk County, Ontario]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1794]]\n[[Category:1794 establishments in the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Populated places on Lake Erie in Canada]]\n", "name_user": "Jo-Jo Eumerus", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing link(s):Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/Paris Port Dover Pipe Bandclosed as delete (XFDcloser)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Port_Dover,_Ontario"}
